displayName.text: Consulate General of the People's Republic of China in New York

adrFormatAddress: 520 12th Ave, New York, NY 10036, USA

originalText.text:
The time on your online reservation doesn't mean anything. You have to line up once you pass the security to have a lady check all your docs and get a number if your package is complete. Come as early as 8:30 am to line up if you don't want to waste too much time here. The windows inside open at 9 but they will let you in near 8:40.

Get your online application printed otherwise you will be turned away.

originalText.text:
I was pleasantly surprised how fast I was seen to and at the speedy turnaround for procressing and pickup, so I wanted to add to the positive reviews.

It's my first time applying for the visa as a Chinese-American adult. I referred to the r/ChinaVisa subreddit and the US-China Embassy website for "Requirements and Procedures for China Visa application" for all the documents I needed. I saw many warnings about having photocopies ready, so I went and printed them out on my own at the library before heading over for walk-in. Surprisingly, they didn't need the physical copies of my photo I took for the COVA application. Take that as you will ;)

I expected a long line because I came in on a Tuesday afternoon about two hours before closing, but I only had to wait 15-20 minutes for my turn. Security let me in right away (i.e., I skipped bag check) when I told them I was there for the visa application. A receptionist thumbed through all the documents I had and asked me about any previous visas. It was the only minor setback I had, and I was warned it might take longer for someone to see me, which I said I was fine with.

Thankfully, when I went up to a window, the employee told me they simply needed my Chinese name that was used for my previous visa, and gave me time to write it down on the COVA form. I had to step away to make a quick phone call to confirm the needed information, so the employee told me they would see to the next ticket, and that I could come back to the window once I was ready to continue; I appreciated that efficiency since it meant more people could be seen to at a time without delay (although I understand others might see this as a bad thing lol but I don't like inconveniencing others). I only had to wait about three minutes for that next person to be seen to before it was my turn again.

My Chinese has become pretty rusty since COVID started due to lack of opportunities to use the language, so I appreciated that the employees had good English and did not pressure me to speak Mandarin.

I saw that regular processing usually takes 1-2 weeks, but maybe because I'm Chinese-American and was applying for the Q2 (invited to visit by a Chinese relative), they told me it'd only take three days to come back and pickup my passport. I was so shocked...!!

Also, I had to use the restroom before leaving and it was super clean. I wanted to give a shoutout to their cleaning team too since usually public bathrooms are nasty.

I know this seems like an overly positive review and not everyone may share the same experience. But this internet stranger hopes that your process can go as smoothly as mine did. :)

Thanks to the staff at the Consulate and happy Chinese new year~

originalText.text:
For the folk who first time applying a Chinese visa, this place has a lack of support for you all. Most of all USA born WITH Chinese parents. To start, the first-timers, who come in person are forced out and to apply online.
When you are done applying online you think you have the application code and just go back, but they want you to print it out over having it through their computer.

Like could they just have a paper form application in place? Also, you need to print it out, the only place you could print costs 1$ each paper.
Also, the first gate won't let you in till you do with application then the stuff inside see you.

The people who went over with this application have Chinese parents. Again you are forced out and get more paper and documents, expecting the younger folks who are in college or LOOK young and disregard passport age. They see us as minors and make it more work for us and get us to obtain documents for minors (18 and under, not 18).

They make this more complicated than it has to. In addition to whatever you bring in to them, they expect you are done but they will try to get you to print more paper, where the printing is already a scam even the printer inside. Also, you won't know if you need documents about Chinese parents till you are inside.

++No tech indoor, phone and computer
++ only open from 9 to 3, 6 hours

To summarize, they need to print paper for the folks who need to be there to apply rather than making them come back. They want speed with online application and yet they need paper. Lack of support for posters outside for Chinese parents to support with what they need.

I came back this place 6 time in the city with 20$ wasted on local printer.

originalText.text: Wow talk about efficiency!! If you have all your documents printed out (if not there is a photocopy machine for 25cents per page) then you will be seen and taken care of promptly. No lines and open windows when I went in, so in and out in less than 10 minutes!!

originalText.text:
This is what you need when applying for a Chinese Visa besides the Application form (they are not very clear online)

1. Passport (they will keep until the visa is approved, typically 4 business days)
2. Proof of residency in New York (a bill or lease will suffice)
3. Copy of tickets in and out of China & Travel itinerary inside China.
4. Letter of Invite (if applicable)
5. Confirmation of appointment (schedule one online after you’ve filled out the application, if you don’t see the option for this online, you filled out the wrong application. It’s called COVA)
6. If your parents are Chinese and we’re naturalized American, but you were born in America, you need to provide your birth certificate and both of their certificates of Naturalization.

If you missed anything or need something printed out, you can print them out at Freedom News across the street for $1 a page.

Went on a Friday and Saturday morning right at 9am. Wait wasn’t too bad if you have all the paperwork ready.

Security and staff were really nice and helpful. 3/5 because the website is unclear about what you need to bring, essentially making you run across the street 2-4 times printing out documents you didn’t know you needed.
